'''Sir John Irving Bell''', [[Royal Society|FRS]], [[Academy of Medical Sciences|FMedSci]] (born 1 July 1952<ref name="debretts">{{cite web | url = http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/b/6667/John+Irving.aspx | title = Prof Sir John Bell | publisher = Debretts | accessdate = 3 January 2013}}</ref>) is a Canadian [[immunologist]] and [[geneticist]] who resides in the UK.<ref name=CV>[http://www.med.lu.se/content/download/481/3256/file/cv_john_bell.pdf Curriculum vitae: John Irving Bell] (accessed 21 December 2008)</ref> From 2006 to 2011, he was President of the [[Academy of Medical Sciences]], and since 2002 has held the [[Regius Professor of Medicine (Oxford)|Regius Chair of Medicine]] at [[Oxford University]], UK.<ref name=Watts>{{cite pmid| 19027476 }}</ref>

==Education and career==
Bell was born in [[Edmonton]], [[Canada]], where his parents worked in [[haematology]] and [[pharmacy]].<ref name=Watts /> He graduated from the [[University of Alberta]] in 1975,  and then studied medicine on a [[Rhodes Scholarship]] at [[Oxford University]].<ref name=Watts /> In 1982, he took up a position as Clinical Fellow in Immunology with [[Hugh McDevitt]] at [[Stanford University]], [[California]], USA, where he worked on [[histocompatibility antigens]] and [[autoimmune disease]].<ref name=Watts /><ref name=AMS_bio>[http://www.acmedsci.ac.uk/p34.html Professor John Bell, PMedSci – A Biographical Note], 21 December 2008)</ref><ref name=OHA_bio>[http://www.oxha.org/about/board-of-trustees/john-bell The Oxford Health Alliance: Sir John Bell] (accessed 21 December 2008)</ref>

In 1987 Bell returned to Oxford as a [[Wellcome Trust]] Senior Clinical Fellow, and joined the [[Institute of Molecular Medicine]], founded by [[David Weatherall]]. In 1992 he succeeded Weatherall as the Nuffield Professor of Clinical Medicine and, in 2002, became the [[Regius Professor of Medicine (Oxford)|Regius Professor of Medicine]] at Oxford, also after Weatherall. In 1994, Bell was one of the founders of the [[Wellcome Trust Centre for Human Genetics]] at Oxford University.<ref name=Watts /><ref name=AMS_bio /> He is a fellow of [[Magdalen College, Oxford]].<ref name=OHA_bio />

==Directorships & controversies, consulting and charity positions==
Bell has been a non-executive director of [[Hoffmann–La Roche|Roche]] since 2001.<ref>[http://www.roche.com/about_roche/management/board_of_directors.htm Roche: Board of Directors] (accessed 21 December 2008)</ref> He serves on the scientific advisory board of Roche Palo Alto (from 1998), and formerly served on that of [[AstraZeneca]] (1997–2000).<ref name=AMS_bio /> He was the founding director of three [[biotechnology]] companies.<ref name=Watts /><ref name=AMS_bio /> 


According to the Roche Finance report of 2011 Bell was paid €322 450 in 2011 for his non-executive director role <ref>www.roche.com/investors/annual_reports/annual_reports_2011.htm: Finance Report (accessed 24 March 2013)  </ref> Controversially he has failed to use his role in Roche to make available the results of unpublished studies on Tamiflu to researchers. This has led some to ask "What do Roche and its shareholders expect for this level of involvement and remuneration?" <ref>www.bmj.com/content/345/bmj.e8351: BMJ 2012 </ref>


His charity positions include chairing the board of trustees of the [[Oxford Health Alliance]] and the science committee of the [[UK Biobank]].<ref name=OHA_bio /><ref>[http://www.ukbiobank.ac.uk/about/team/directors.php UK Biobank: Board of Directors] (accessed 21 December 2008)</ref>

==Research==
Bell's research has identified genes involved in susceptibility to [[diabetes mellitus type 1]] and [[rheumatoid arthritis]]. His work has been important in elucidating the interactions on the surface of the [[T cell]] involved in immune activation. He has also worked on the biomedical applications of [[High-throughput screening|high-throughput genomic technologies]], including [[structural genomics]] and [[ENU]] [[mutagenesis]].<ref name=AMS_bio />

==Awards and honours==
Bell was awarded an honorary [[D.Sc.]] by the [[University of Alberta]] in 2003.<ref>[http://www.uofaweb.ualberta.ca/senate/honorarydegreeslist.cfm#B University of Alberta: Past Honorary Degree Recipients: B] (accessed 21 December 2008)</ref> He was President of the [[Academy of Medical Sciences]] from 2006-2011.<ref name=Watts /><ref>[http://www.acmedsci.ac.uk/p108.html The Academy of Medical Sciences: Governance: Honorary Officers] (accessed 23 July 2012)</ref> In 2008, he was elected a fellow of the [[Royal Society]],<ref>[http://royalsociety.org/DServe/dserve.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqCmd=Show.tcl&dsqDb=Persons&dsqPos=6&dsqSearch=((text)%3D%27Bell%27) Royal Society: Library and Archive catalogue: Bell; John Irving; Sir] (accessed 21 December 2008)</ref><ref>[http://royalsociety.org/publication.asp?id=7713 Royal Society: New Fellows – 2008: Agarwal–Cohen] (accessed 21 December 2008)</ref> and was knighted for services to medicine in the [[New Year Honours 2008|New Year Honours]] of that year.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/bsp/hi/pdfs/29_12_07_hons_queen.pdf BBC: 29/12/07 honours list] (accessed 21 December 2008)</ref>

